    <h1>Professional LG Gas Dryer Igniter Repair Service in Los Angeles</h1>
    <p>When your LG gas dryer runs but won't heat, nine times out of ten our technicians find a failed igniter. These ceramic components crack from repeated heating cycles, leaving you with clothes that tumble endlessly but never dry.</p>
<h2>Signs Your LG Dryer Igniter Needs Replacement</h2>
<p>The most obvious sign is a dryer that runs through complete cycles without producing heat. Our techs see this constantly — homeowners think it's a gas problem, but the igniter has simply cracked internally. You might hear the dryer running normally, feel air movement, but clothes come out damp every time. Some igniters glow orange for a few seconds then shut off without lighting the gas. This happens when the ceramic element can't draw enough current to signal the gas valve. Don't confuse this with a clogged vent — that causes overheating and automatic shutdowns. A bad igniter lets the dryer complete its cycle but produces zero heat.</p>
<h3>Visual Inspection Warning Signs</h3>
<p>Never attempt to visually inspect the igniter while the dryer is running. Our technicians always disconnect power first. A cracked igniter might glow briefly then go dark, or show visible cracks along the ceramic surface when cool.</p>
<h2>Tools and Parts Required for LG Dryer Igniter Replacement</h2>
<p>This repair requires specific tools most homeowners don't have. Our techs carry quarter-inch and five-sixteenths nut drivers, needle-nose pliers, and a multimeter for testing. The critical component is the OEM LG igniter — aftermarket versions fail within months because they can't handle the exact amperage requirements. We stock genuine LG parts for all major series including DLGX and DLEX models. Each LG dryer model uses a specific igniter with precise mounting dimensions. The wrong part might physically fit but won't create the proper electrical signal to open the gas valve. Installation also requires understanding the safety circuit — the igniter must reach exact temperature before gas flows.</p>
<h3>Why OEM Parts Matter for Safety</h3>
<p>Gas appliances aren't the place for generic parts. Our technicians have seen aftermarket igniters that either fail to light gas consistently or create delayed ignition — both dangerous conditions that can damage your dryer or worse.</p>
<h2>Step-by-Step LG Dryer Igniter Installation Process</h2>
<p>Professional installation starts with complete power disconnection and gas line shutoff. Our technicians remove the dryer's lower front panel to access the burner assembly. The igniter mounts directly to the gas valve housing with two screws and connects via a two-wire harness. Removing the old igniter requires careful handling — even non-functional ones are extremely fragile. The new OEM igniter must be positioned exactly as the original, with proper clearance from the gas tube. After installation, we test the entire sequence: igniter glows, gas valve opens, flame lights, igniter shuts off. This process should take exactly forty-five to sixty seconds on properly functioning LG dryers.</p>
<h3>Critical Safety Steps During Installation</h3>
<p>Gas line work requires specific safety protocols. Our technicians always check for gas leaks after reconnection using approved leak detection solution. One small leak can create a serious hazard, which is why this repair isn't recommended for DIY attempts.</p>
<h2>Testing Your New LG Dryer Igniter After Installation</h2>
<p>Proper testing goes beyond just seeing if the dryer heats up. Our technicians run multiple cycles to verify consistent ignition timing and flame characteristics. The igniter should glow bright orange within thirty seconds, maintain that glow for another fifteen seconds, then the gas should light immediately. Any delayed ignition indicates a problem with gas pressure or valve operation. We also check that the igniter shuts off completely once the burner is lit — continued glowing wastes energy and shortens component life. Temperature testing ensures the dryer reaches proper heat levels throughout the cycle. Many homeowners in Pasadena call us thinking their new igniter is defective when it's actually working perfectly but they have a separate airflow restriction.</p>
<h3>Understanding Normal Igniter Operation</h3>
<p>A functioning igniter cycles on and off throughout the drying process. It's normal to see the glow, hear gas ignition, then see the glow disappear. This happens multiple times per cycle as the dryer maintains temperature.</p>
<h2>When Professional Repair Beats DIY Replacement</h2>
<p>Most igniter failures aren't actually igniter problems — they're symptoms of other issues. Our diagnostic process identifies the root cause before replacing parts. Gas valve problems, thermal fuse issues, or control board malfunctions can all mimic igniter failure. Homeowners who replace the igniter without proper diagnosis often face the same problem weeks later. Professional repair also includes safety testing that prevents dangerous conditions. We've responded to calls in Orange County where DIY igniter replacement resulted in gas leaks or electrical problems. The $65 diagnostic fee gets waived when you proceed with repair, making professional service cost-effective compared to multiple parts purchases and potential safety hazards.</p>
<h3>Hidden Costs of DIY Repair Attempts</h3>
<p>Beyond the safety risks, DIY repairs often create additional problems. Wrong parts, damaged connections, or missed safety checks can turn a simple igniter replacement into a major repair requiring multiple service calls.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<h3>How do I know if my LG dryer igniter is bad?</h3>
<p>The classic sign is a dryer that runs complete cycles but produces no heat. Our technicians see this constantly — the drum tumbles, you hear normal operation, but clothes come out damp. Sometimes you'll see the igniter glow orange for a few seconds then go dark without lighting the gas. Don't try to diagnose this yourself by looking inside while it's running. We always disconnect power first, then test the igniter's electrical resistance with a multimeter.</p>
<h3>Can I replace an LG dryer igniter myself?</h3>
<p>We strongly advise against DIY igniter replacement. This involves working with gas lines and high-voltage electrical connections. Our technicians have responded to calls where homeowners created gas leaks or damaged the control circuitry during attempted repairs. Beyond safety concerns, most igniter failures are actually caused by other components — replacing just the igniter without proper diagnosis usually doesn't solve the problem.</p>
<h3>How much does an LG dryer igniter replacement cost?</h3>
<p>Our total repair cost typically runs between $180-240 depending on your specific LG model. That includes the OEM igniter part, installation, safety testing, and our standard warranty. The $65 diagnostic fee gets waived when you proceed with repair. Aftermarket parts might seem cheaper upfront, but we've seen them fail within months because they can't handle LG's specific electrical requirements.</p>
<h3>How long should an LG dryer igniter last?</h3>
<p>With normal use, OEM LG igniters typically last eight to twelve years. Our technicians see premature failure when homeowners run oversized loads constantly or have restricted airflow from clogged vents. Each heating cycle puts stress on the ceramic element, so frequent short cycles actually cause more wear than fewer long ones. Proper maintenance and using appropriate load sizes definitely extends igniter life.</p>
<h3>What tools do I need to replace an LG dryer igniter?</h3>
<p>Professional replacement requires quarter-inch and five-sixteenths nut drivers, needle-nose pliers, a multimeter for testing, and most importantly — proper gas leak detection equipment. Our technicians also carry specialized tools for safely handling the fragile ceramic igniter and testing the gas valve operation. The bigger issue isn't having tools, it's having the knowledge to properly diagnose the problem and safely work with gas appliances.</p>
